1. Problem Statement¶

You are consulting for a real estate company that has a niche in purchasing properties to rent out short-term as part of their business model specifically within New York City. The real estate company has already concluded that two bedroom properties are the most profitable; however, they do not know which zip codes are the best to invest in.

The real estate company has engaged your firm to build out a data product and provide your conclusions to help them understand which zip codes would generate the most profit on short term rentals within New York City.

2. Defining Profitability¶

For this problem, we define profitability as:

  • Long term perspective:
    • Capacity to generate the largest incremental profit in the long run
  • Short term perspective:
    • Least time taken to break-even with the initial investment

3. Executive Summary¶

  • Investment in property is most profitable around the Upper East Side of Manhattan (ZIP codes: 10028, 10128) in terms of breaking even from initial investment the earliest, as well as in term of greater incremental profits in the long run.
    • An investment in a property in this area is estimated to break-even in around 6 years, and be valued at ~$2M USD (in profits) in around 12 years (inclusive of revenue from short term Airbnb rentals).
  • Investment in property is also highly profitable around the southern side of the Upper East Side of Manhattan (ZIP code: 10022) and around the Upper West Side of Manhattan (ZIP code: 10023).
    • An investment in a property in this area is estimated to break-even in around 8 years, and be valued at ~$1.3M USD (in profits) in around 12 years (inclusive of revenue from short term Airbnb rentals).
  • Diversification of investment among these ZIP codes is highly recommended to minimize risk.

4. Assumptions Made¶

  • Fixed Assumptions:
    • The investor will pay for the property in cash (i.e. no mortgage/interest rate will be accounted for)
    • The time value of money / discount rate is 0%
  • Additional Assumption:
    • There is no seasonal effect on AirBnb occupancy rates. Hence the short term occupancy rate for an Airbnb listing is derived from the number of days available to book within the next 30 days (Column: 'availability_30')
    • Current period of time is May, 2017

In [10]:
# Filter out the extreme outliers
q25,q75 = airbnb_sub_2["price"].quantile([0.25,0.75]).values
iqr = q75 - q25
upper_bound_outlier = q75 + 1.5*iqr
lower_bound_outlier = q25 - 1.5*iqr
airbnb_no_outliers = airbnb_sub_2[(airbnb_sub_2['price'] < upper_bound_outlier) & (airbnb_sub_2['price'] > lower_bound_outlier)]
print('Dimensions after outlier treatment:',airbnb_no_outliers.shape)
print('% of data retained post treatment', airbnb_no_outliers.shape[0]/airbnb_sub_2.shape[0])
ax = sns.boxplot(x="neighbourhood_group_cleansed", y="price", data=airbnb_no_outliers)

It is observed from the above 2 tables that, before the outlier treatment, boroughs like Manhattan have the difference between mean and median around ~$50.¶

Whereas, after the outlier removal, the difference between mean and median is only ~$15 or less for all boroughs.¶

Hence, the median of Airbnb rent ('price') will be the aggregating methodology for this analysis to take a more conservative approach.¶

It is observed that 1 or 2 ZIP codes are mapped to multiple boroughs.¶

Hence, these ZIP code(s) are assigned to it's 'true' borough, which is found after a study on NYC geographies.¶

Post the correction, since the primary objective is concerning ZIP codes, 2 main datasets are then created. One at an Airbnb listing level, and the other at a ZIP code aggregated level.¶

airbnb_listing.describe()['availability_30']

# zipcode, neighbourhood_group_cleansed, median price level, num_listings
airbnb_zip = airbnb_listing.groupby(['zipcode','neighbourhood_group_cleansed'],as_index=False).agg({'price':np.median, 'id':'count', 'availability_30':np.mean})

# renaming columns

airbnb_listing = airbnb_listing.rename(columns={'price':'airbnb_price', 'neighbourhood_group_cleansed':'Borough', 'availability_30':'occupancy_rate'})

# function to plot a bar and line chart
def bar_line(x1,x_label, y1,y1_label, y1_label_format, y2,y2_label,y2_label_format, titl, colr):
    y1_max = (y1.max()*1.2)
    p = figure(title=titl, x_range=x1.unique(), y_range= (0,y1_max), plot_height=400, x_axis_label=x_label, y_axis_label=y1_label)
    
    p.yaxis[0].formatter = NumeralTickFormatter(format=y1_label_format)
    p.vbar(x=x1.unique(), top=y1.unique(), width=0.9, alpha=0.5, legend=y1_label, color=colr)
    y2_max = (y2.max()+500)
    p.extra_y_ranges = {"foo": Range1d(start=0, end=y2_max)}
    p.line(x=x1.unique(), y=y2.unique(), color="red", line_width=3,
       legend=y2_label, y_range_name="foo")
    p.circle(x=x1.unique(), y=y2.unique(), line_color="red", fill_color="white",
         size=10, y_range_name="foo")
    p.add_layout(LinearAxis(y_range_name="foo", axis_label=y2_label),'right')
    p.yaxis[1].formatter = NumeralTickFormatter(format=y2_label_format)
    show(p)

From the above chart, it is observed that most Airbnb listings are located in Brooklyn and Manhattan.¶

It is also noted that listings in Manhattan have a higher Airbnb rent on average, than that of the other boroughs i.e. listings in Manhattan have a higher earning capacity.¶

Rent in the other 3 boroughs are also found to be competitive to that of Brooklyn's, but have fewer number of listings. This may indicate a sign of demand not being met, and may prove to be an opportunity.¶

Similar to the trend in Airbnb rent, Manhattan, followed by Brooklyn, also appears to have the highest occupancy rate on average. This again supports the theory of high earning capacity for Airbnb listings in Manhattan.¶

The fair occupancy rates of around 60% in the other 3 boroughs, along with a competitve Airbnb rent and low number of listings, again puts forward the theory of an unrealized opportunity.¶

def geo_plot2(data, num_plots, y1, y1_color, y1_title, y2, y2_color, y2_title):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (25,10), ncols=num_plots)
    data.plot(column=y1, cmap=y1_color, alpha=10, linewidth=.1, ax=ax[0], legend=True, edgecolor='black')
    ax[0].set_title(y1_title, size=20)
    data.plot(column=y2, cmap=y2_color, alpha=10, linewidth=.1, ax=ax[1], legend=True, edgecolor='black')
    ax[1].set_title(y2_title, size=20)
    plt.show()

It is found that the extreme variations from ZIP codes in Staten Island are caused by very few data points (num_listings) supporting them. Hence, ZIP codes with less than 10 listings are filtered out. A profitability index is then created to better visualize the profitability.¶

In [32]:
# creating profitability index though inverse min max scaling of risk
zip_prof_index = pd.DataFrame(zip_cost[['zipcode','break_even_years','num_listings']])
# considering only zip codes with more than 10 listings
zip_prof_index = zip_prof_index[zip_prof_index['num_listings'] > 10]
mx = zip_prof_index.break_even_years.max()
mn = zip_prof_index.break_even_years.min()
zip_prof_index['scaled_risk'] = (zip_prof_index['break_even_years']-mn)/(mx-mn)
zip_prof_index['profit_index'] = 1-zip_prof_index['scaled_risk']
zip_prof_zip = pd.merge(pd.DataFrame(airbnb_zip['zipcode']), zip_prof_index, how='left', left_on='zipcode', right_on='zipcode')
zip_prof_zip = zip_prof_zip.fillna(0)

We observe that properties located around Manhattan and Brooklyn take the least amount of time to break-even, as compared to other areas in New York City.¶

It is also noted that relying solely on the revenue from Airbnb rentals require 20+ years to break-even with the initial investment. Hence, we forgo analyzing the profitability in the long run, and proceed to analyze the influence of real estate value over time, on profitability.¶

A parameter grid is then created to run a 'grid search' to find the optimal set of parameters that yeilds the best performance for the model. The parameters are selected based on the model that generates the lowest AIC.¶

In [38]:
# creating a grid of parameters
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
p = d = q = range(0, 2)
pdq = list(itertools.product(p, d, q))
seasonal_pdq = [(x[0], x[1], x[2], 12) for x in list(itertools.product(p, d, q))]
# choosing the best parameters (grid search)
best_aic = 1000000.00
for param in pdq:
    for param_seasonal in seasonal_pdq:
        try:
            mod = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(y,
                                            order=param,
                                            seasonal_order=param_seasonal,
                                            enforce_stationarity=False,
                                            enforce_invertibility=False)
            results = mod.fit()
            if results.aic < best_aic:
                best_para = param
                best_para_seas = param_seasonal
                best_aic = results.aic
        except:
            continue

An ARIMA time series model is now created for all the remaining zip codes¶

In [45]:
for i in range(1,15):
    y = zillow_ts_zip_line.iloc[:,i]
    y_col_name = zillow_ts_zip_line.columns[i]
    best_aic = 1000000.00
    for param in pdq:
        for param_seasonal in seasonal_pdq:
            try:
                mod = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(y, order=param, seasonal_order=param_seasonal, enforce_stationarity=False, enforce_invertibility=False)
                results = mod.fit()
                if results.aic < best_aic:
                    best_para = param
                    best_para_seas = param_seasonal
                    best_aic = results.aic
            except:
                continue
    mod = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(y, order=best_para, seasonal_order=best_para_seas, enforce_stationarity=False, enforce_invertibility=False)
    results = mod.fit()
    # checking rmse
    pred = results.get_prediction(start=pd.to_datetime('2012-01-01'), dynamic=False)
    y_forecasted = pred.predicted_mean
    y_truth = y['2012-01-01':]
    mse = ((y_forecasted - y_truth) ** 2).mean()
    print('The Root Mean Squared Error of the forecast of zip code {} is {}'.format(y_col_name,'${:,.2f}'.format(round(np.sqrt(mse), 2))))
    #make predictions
    pred_uc = results.get_forecast(steps=200)
    #find NPV over time
    forecast_1 = pd.DataFrame(pred_uc.predicted_mean, columns=[str(y_col_name)])
    forecast_1_npv = forecast_1
    forecast_1_npv['Current_price'] = float(zip_cost[zip_cost['zipcode']==y_col_name]['Current_price'])
    forecast_1_npv['monthly_revenue'] = float((zip_cost[zip_cost['zipcode']==y_col_name]['annual_revenue'])/12)
    forecast_1_npv['NPV_pre'] = (-forecast_1_npv['Current_price']) + (forecast_1_npv[str(y_col_name)] - forecast_1_npv['Current_price']) + forecast_1_npv['monthly_revenue']
    forecast_1_npv['NPV'] = forecast_1_npv['NPV_pre'].shift(1) + forecast_1_npv['monthly_revenue']
    forecast_zip = pd.DataFrame(forecast_1_npv['NPV']).rename(columns={'NPV':y_col_name})
    # merge to master predicted dataframe
    forecast_final = pd.merge(forecast_final, forecast_zip, how='inner', left_index=True, right_index=True)

10. Recommendations¶

  • Investments in property should primarily be made around the Upper East Side of Manhattan (ZIP codes: 10028, 10128).

  • Investments in property, subject to additional availability of capital, should also be made around the southern area of the Upper East Side of Manhattan (ZIP code: 10022) and around the Upper West Side of Manhattan (ZIP code: 10023).

  • Diversification of investment among these ZIP codes is highly recommended to minimize risk.
